data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** (or `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`). It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require no migration.

That said, for modern .NET you'd typically replace raw threads with `Task.Run` + `Parallel.ForEachAsync`, which gives you cleaner cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you ever need it:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

But that's a modernization choice, not a required migration. Your current code will compile and run on .NET 8 as-is.
